			<p>Catering for fifty people sounds simple until you're standing in a kitchen at 11:45 AM realising the food is late, the dietary labels are missing, and the meeting starts in fifteen minutes. After fifteen years of <a href="/corporate">catering Vancouver offices</a> — from boardroom lunches to all-hands gatherings — we've learned that big group catering is less about quantity and more about discipline.</p>

			<h2>Get the <em>Headcount</em> Three Days Out</h2>
			<p>The single biggest source of stress in office catering is unclear guest counts. We always recommend confirming a final number 48–72 hours before the event. Too late and the kitchen scrambles. Too early and you risk over-ordering.</p>
			<p>Build a rhythm: send the calendar invite a week out, send a reminder for RSVPs three days before, lock the count two days before delivery. This small discipline solves 80% of office catering problems.</p>

			<h2>Always Plan for <em>10–15% More</em></h2>
			<p>Even with confirmed RSVPs, plan for slightly more food than your final headcount. For 50 confirmed guests, plan portions for 55–60. The extra cost is minimal and the alternative — running out of food — is far worse.</p>

			<h2>Dietary Restrictions <em>Aren't Optional</em></h2>
			<p>For any office of 50+ people, you'll have a mix of vegetarians, vegans, gluten-free, halal, and probably at least one nut allergy. What works:</p>
			<ul>
				<li>Always include a vegetarian main, ideally vegan</li>
				<li>Have at least one gluten-free option clearly labelled</li>
				<li>For halal needs, work with a caterer that <a href="/blog/halal-indian-catering-vancouver">sources halal-certified meats</a> by default</li>
				<li>Label every dish with allergens</li>
				<li>Ask about restrictions in your RSVP form, not in the room</li>
			</ul>

			<h2>Hot Food Needs <em>Hot Delivery</em></h2>
			<p>Indian food is at its best when it's hot. Lukewarm dal makhani is sad dal makhani. Ask your caterer specifically how they transport hot food — the answer should involve insulated, temperature-controlled containers.</p>
			<p>If the food has to sit for an hour before service, ask about chafing dish setup. For meetings of 50+, a simple buffet line with two chafing dishes per hot course will keep things flowing.</p>

			<h2>Buffet vs. <em>Boxed Meals</em></h2>
			<p>For meetings under 90 minutes, individually packed boxed meals often work better than buffets. People grab and go, the meeting starts on time, and there's no buffet line bottleneck.</p>
			<p>For longer events — half-day workshops, all-hands, conferences — a buffet creates better energy. The trade-off is a 15-minute serving window.</p>

			<h2>The Indian Menu That <em>Always Works</em></h2>
			<p>After hundreds of Vancouver office lunches, here's the menu structure that consistently delivers — see our <a href="/blog/best-indian-dishes-corporate-lunches">complete list of best dishes</a>:</p>
			<ul>
				<li>One vegetarian curry that's a crowd-pleaser (paneer butter masala, palak paneer, dal makhani)</li>
				<li>One non-vegetarian curry (chicken tikka masala or butter chicken)</li>
				<li>One rice (basmati or pulao)</li>
				<li>One bread (naan or roti)</li>
				<li>A starter or chaat counter for variety</li>
				<li>One simple dessert (gulab jamun, ras malai, or kheer)</li>
				<li>Salad and pickles on the side</li>
			</ul>

			<h2>Recurring Programs <em>Save Time</em></h2>
			<p>If your team eats together regularly, set up a rotating menu with your caterer. We work with several Vancouver companies on weekly programs where the menu rotates through 6–8 chef's selections. Add a <a href="/cafe-catering">chai or coffee station</a> for all-day events.</p>

			<h2>Final Thoughts</h2>
			<p>Office catering isn't glamorous, but it's deeply important. A well-fed team works better, longer, and happier. The difference is rarely the food itself — it's the discipline behind getting it right.</p>
